Vice President Kamala Harris addressed the National Space Council at the Andrew Mellon Auditorium in Washington, D.C. She thanked Colonel Hansen and the Artemis 2 astronauts for their work in leading the nation and the world back to the Moon. Harris recognized the United States Space Force on its fourth anniversary and applauded the Guardians in attendance. She emphasized the importance of strengthening international partnerships in space exploration and outlined three priorities: tackling the climate crisis, establishing new international rules and norms, and advancing human space exploration. Harris discussed the use of space data to fight against climate change and announced plans to launch a satellite to collect air pollution data in the Southern Hemisphere. She also highlighted the need for international rules and norms for the peaceful and responsible use of space, including the commitment to not conduct destructive anti-satellite missile testing. Harris mentioned the Artemis Accords and the development of a regulatory framework for commercial space activities. Finally, she announced the intention to land an international astronaut on the Moon by the end of the decade and emphasized the importance of international collaboration in the Artemis program.